# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: code-splitting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] In marketing, **product bundling** is offering several products or services for sale as one combined product or service package.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] It is a common feature in many imperfectly competitive product and service markets.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Industries engaged in the practice include telecommunications services, financial services, health care, information, and consumer electronics.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] A software bundle might include a word processor, spreadsheet, and presentation program into a single office suite.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] The cable television industry often bundles many TV and movie channels into a single tier or package.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] The fast food industry combines separate food items into a "combo meal" or "value meal".
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Unbundling refers to the process of breaking up packages of products and services which were previously offered as a group or bundle.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] A bundle of products may be called a **package deal**; in recorded music or video games, a **compilation** or box set; or in publishing, an **anthology**.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Product bundling is most suitable for high volume and high margin (i.e., low marginal cost) products.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Research by Yannis Bakos and Erik Brynjolfsson found that bundling was particularly effective for digital information goods with close to zero marginal cost, and could enable a bundler with an inferior collection of products to drive even superior quality goods out of the market place.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Most firms are multi-product or multi-service companies faced with the decision whether to sell products or services separately at individual prices or whether combinations of products should be marketed in the form of "bundles" for which a "bundle price" is asked.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Price bundling plays an increasingly important role in many industries (e.g. banking, insurance, software, automotive) and some companies even build their business strategies on bundling.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] In bundle pricing, companies sell a package or set of goods or services for a lower price than they would charge if the customer bought all of them separately.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Pursuing a bundle pricing strategy allows a business to increase its profit by using a discount to induce customers to buy more than they otherwise would have.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] While many well-known examples of bundling are all products or services from the same store or provider, such as the sports package for a car or a grocery store's gift basket, in some cases, cross-industry bundles are assembled and sold.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] For example, some travel agencies have vacation tour bundles that may include air tickets, rail tickets, a rental car, hotels, restaurants, museum and sightseeing attraction tickets and live music event tickets.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] These bundles include products and services from the transportation, accommodation, tourism, food service and entertainment industries.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Consumers have heterogeneous demands and such demands for different parts of the bundle product are inversely correlated.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] For example, assume consumer A values a word processor software at $100 and a spreadsheet processor at $60, while consumer B values a word processor at $60 and spreadsheet at $100.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Seller can generate a maximum revenue of only $240 by setting a $60 price for each product—both consumers will buy both products.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Revenue cannot be increased without bundling because as the seller increases the price above $60 for one of the goods, one of the consumers will refuse to buy it.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] With bundling, a seller can generate revenue of $320 by bundling the products together and selling the bundle at $160.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Thus, bundling can be considered a form of price discrimination.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Venkatesh and Mahajan reviewed the research on bundle design and pricing in 2009.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Bundling is often thought of mainly as a value pricing strategy, in that product bundles often cost less than if each item were purchased separately.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] However, bundling can also have other strategic advantages.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] For example, when a grocery store is making up a gift basket, they can use the design of the basket item list as a way to promote new products or brands that a customer may not know or as a way to liquidate merchandise that is not selling well.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] A well-off home theatre enthusiast with a very high budget may find a $10,000 home theatre package attractive, even if it costs a bit more than buying each item separately, because this is an impressive total cost.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Pure bundling occurs when a consumer can only purchase the entire bundle or nothing at all.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Mixed bundling occurs when consumers are offered a choice between purchasing the entire bundle or one of the separate parts of the bundle, and mixed-leader bundling is a variant of leader bundling with the added possibility of buying the leader product on its own.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] In the computer industry, **bundled software** is distributed with another product such as a piece of computer hardware or other electronic device, or is a group of software packages which are sold together.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Software which is pre-installed on a new computer is an example of bundled software.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] For example, as of 2017, most desktop, laptop and mobile computers are bought pre-loaded with various software and software applications ("apps").
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] A pack-in game is a form of bundled software.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Early microcomputer companies varied in their decision to bundle software.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] *BYTE* in 1984 observed that "Kaypro apparently has tremendous buying and bargaining power", noting that the Kaypro 10 came with both WordStar and Perfect Writer, plus "two spelling checkers, two spreadsheets, two communications programs and three versions of BASIC".
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Compaq, by contrast, did not bundle software, stating that "You remove the freedom from the dealers to really merchandise when you bundle in software ...
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Why should you be constrained to use the software that comes with a piece of hardware?
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] I think it can tend to inhibit sales over the long run." MacWrite's inclusion with early Macintosh computers discouraged developers from creating other word processing software for the computer.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Many companies sold multimedia upgrade kits—a CD-ROM drive, sound card, speakers, and what *Computer Gaming World* described as "a boatload of bundled software"—during the mid-1990s.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] In the 1990s and in the 2000s (decade) and 2010s, many consumer electronics companies designed home theatre equipment bundles, known as Home Theatre in a Box (HTIB).
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] For a customer who already owned a TV, and in some cases a DVD player or other source for playing back movies, a HTIB package provides all of the electronics hardware, speakers and cables needed to set up a home cinema.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] There are three grades of HTIB bundles: economy bundles, aimed at the lowest price point; mid-tier bundles, the most common type; and higher-cost HTIB bundles made by BOSE and other higher-end manufacturers.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] At the economy grade HTIB package, the customer is provided with a basic home theatre set-up, with modest sound quality and relatively few options for adjusting the sound.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] The mid-tier and upper-tier packages offer better performance and more set-up options.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] The most serious home theatre enthusiasts do not typically buy HTIB bundles, as they are a more sophisticated target market.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] As such, the most serious home cinema-philes typically purchase each component (power amplifiers, speakers, subwoofer cabinet, speaker cables) separately, so that they can choose which items meet their specific movie-watching goals.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] For example, a serious home theatre enthusiast may wish to have a large cabinet subwoofer enclosure with heavy bracing, a type and size of subwoofer cabinet that would not be found in any HTIB bundle due to its large size and high cost.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] As well, a serious home theatre enthusiast may wish to have a powered subwoofer with a user-adjustable crossover, a "subsonic" filter and other higher-cost advanced features.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] In oligopolistic and monopolistic industries, product bundling can be seen as an unfair use of market power because it limits the choices available to the consumer.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] In these cases it is typically called product tying.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Some forms of product bundling have been subject to litigation regarding abuses of market share.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Cable and satellite television (Pay TV) have bundled TV channels since the inception of both.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] In the early years of the cable industry this was necessary due to the technological constraints associated with allowing and blocking channels transmitted via analog methods.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] The progress towards complete cable, internet, and telephone packages gave subscribers many more options as well as offering hundreds of channels.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] The "package" price depends on the level of service a customer prefers within each bundle.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] The services range from low speed internet and minimum channels to high speed internet and the addition of many premium channels.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] In the US prices for pay TV have doubled in the last twenty years, averaging 6% per year, while wages have remained the same for nearly 20 years causing dissatisfaction and many cancellations.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Costs have risen 53% since 2007 and Comcast and AT&T's Direct TV went up in January 2018.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] With the Digital television transition opportunities for competition to pay TV ushered in online video companies and forcing pay TV companies to examine à la carte cable company packages.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] A 2018 consumer report shows many subscribers are dissatisfied with cable TV, mainly over prices, which has led to many complaints.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Google Fiber was an exception to widespread consumer dissatisfaction.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Verizon and the two satellite-TV companies —AT&T's DirecTV and Dish Network rated better than Cox Communications, Comcast, Spectrum, Optimum, CenturyLink, SuddenLink Communications, Atlantic Broadband, Frontier Communications, and Mediacom was rated at the bottom.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Internet providers EPB (Fiber Optics) and Google Fiber received top ratings for value.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Of the smaller companies only Armstrong received top ratings and RCN, Hawaiian Telcom (bought by Cincinnati Bell in 2018), and Grande Communications received slightly higher ratings.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] The high price of current complete bundling, upwards of $180–200, along with poor customer service, surprise bills, and technical difficulties, resulted in Angie's List reporting that these things were the number two most complained about category.
[src:code-splitting/bundle-software-distribution] Additionally, reduced-price bundles of streaming service packages, such as The Disney Bundle, are also offered by some providers.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Dynamic loading was a common technique for IBM's operating systems for System/360 such as OS/360, particularly for I/O subroutines, and for COBOL and PL/I runtime libraries, and continues to be used in IBM's operating systems for z/Architecture, such as z/OS.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] As far as the application programmer is concerned, the loading is largely transparent, since it is mostly handled by the operating system (or its I/O subsystem).
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] IBM's strategic transaction processing system, CICS (1970s onwards) uses dynamic loading extensively both for its kernel and for normal application program loading.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Corrections to application programs could be made offline and new copies of changed programs loaded dynamically without needing to restart CICS (which can, and frequently does, run 24/7).
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Shared libraries were added to Unix in the 1980s, but initially without the ability to let a program load additional libraries after startup.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Dynamic loading is most frequently used in implementing software plugins.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] For example, the Apache Web Server's `*.dso` "dynamic shared object" plugin files are libraries which are loaded at runtime with dynamic loading.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Dynamic loading is also used in implementing computer programs where multiple different libraries may supply the requisite functionality and where the user has the option to select which library or libraries to provide.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Not all systems support dynamic loading.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Unix-like operating systems such as macOS, Linux, and Solaris provide dynamic loading with the C programming language "dl" library.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] The Windows operating system provides dynamic loading through the Windows API.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Loading the library is accomplished with `LoadLibrary` or `LoadLibraryEx` on Windows and with `dlopen` on Unix-like operating systems.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Extracting the contents of a dynamically loaded library is achieved with `GetProcAddress` on Windows and with `dlsym` on Unix-like operating systems.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] The result of `dlsym()` or `GetProcAddress()` has to be converted to a pointer of the appropriate type before it can be used.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] This can be problematic when the address of an object is to be retrieved rather than a function.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] However, usually one wants to extract functions anyway, so this is normally not a problem.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] According to the POSIX specification, the result of `dlsym()` is a `void` pointer.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] However, a function pointer is not required to even have the same size as a data object pointer, and therefore a valid conversion between type `void*` and a pointer to a function may not be easy to implement on all platforms.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] On most systems in use today, function and object pointers are *de facto* convertible.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] The above snippet will give a warning on some compilers: `warning: dereferencing type-punned pointer will break strict-aliasing rules`.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] which disables the warning even if strict aliasing is in effect.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] This makes use of the fact that reading from a different union member than the one most recently written to (called "type punning") is common, and explicitly allowed even if strict aliasing is in force, provided the memory is accessed through the union type directly.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] However, this is not strictly the case here, since the function pointer is copied to be used outside the union.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Note that this trick may not work on platforms where the size of data pointers and the size of function pointers is not the same.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] The fact remains that any conversion between function and data object pointers has to be regarded as an (inherently non-portable) implementation extension, and that no "correct" way for a direct conversion exists, since in this regard the POSIX and ISO standards contradict each other.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] For the subsequent version of the standard (issue 7, 2008), the problem has been discussed and the conclusion was that function pointers have to be convertible to `void*` for POSIX compliance.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] This requires compiler makers to implement a working cast for this case.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] If the contents of the library can be changed (i.e. in the case of a custom library), in addition to the function itself a pointer to it can be exported.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Since a pointer to a function pointer is itself an object pointer, this pointer can always be legally retrieved by call to `dlsym()` and subsequent conversion.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] However, this approach requires maintaining separate pointers to all functions that are to be used externally, and the benefits are usually small.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Loading a library causes memory to be allocated; the library must be deallocated in order to avoid a memory leak.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Additionally, failure to unload a library can prevent filesystem operations on the file which contains the library.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Unloading the library is accomplished with `FreeLibrary` on Windows and with `dlclose` on Unix-like operating systems.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] However, unloading a DLL can lead to program crashes if objects in the main application refer to memory allocated within the DLL.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] For example, if a DLL introduces a new class and the DLL is closed, further operations on instances of that class from the main application will likely cause a memory access violation.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Likewise, if the DLL introduces a factory function for instantiating dynamically loaded classes, calling or dereferencing that function after the DLL is closed leads to undefined behaviour.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] The implementations of dynamic loading on Unix-like operating systems and Windows allow programmers to extract symbols from the currently executing process.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Unix-like operating systems allow programmers to access the global symbol table, which includes both the main executable and subsequently loaded dynamic libraries.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Windows allows programmers to access symbols exported by the main executable.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Windows does not use a global symbol table and has no API to search across multiple modules to find a symbol by name.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] In the Java programming language, classes can be dynamically loaded using the **`ClassLoader`** object.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] The Reflection mechanism also provides a means to load a class if it isn't already loaded.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] However, there is no simple way to unload a class in a controlled way.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Loaded classes can only be unloaded in a controlled way, i.e. when the programmer wants this to happen, if the classloader used to load the class is not the system class loader, and is itself unloaded.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] When doing so, various details need to be observed to ensure the class is really unloaded.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] This makes unloading of classes tedious.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Implicit unloading of classes, i.e. in an uncontrolled way by the garbage collector, has changed a few times in Java.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Until Java 1.2. the garbage collector could unload a class whenever it felt it needed the space, independent of which class loader was used to load the class.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Starting with Java 1.2 classes loaded via the system classloader were never unloaded and classes loaded via other classloaders only when this other classloader was unloaded.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Starting with Java 6 classes can contain an internal marker indicating to the garbage collector they can be unloaded if the garbage collector desires to do so, independent of the classloader used to load the class.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] The garbage collector is free to ignore this hint.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Similarly, libraries implementing native methods are dynamically loaded using the `System.loadLibrary` method.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] There is no `System.unloadLibrary` method.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] Despite its promulgation in the 1980s through Unix and Windows, some systems still chose not to add—or even to remove—dynamic loading.
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] For example, Plan 9 from Bell Labs and its successor 9front intentionally avoid dynamic linking, as they consider it to be "harmful".
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] The Go programming language, by some of the same developers as Plan 9, also did not support dynamic linking, but plugin loading is available since Go 1.8 (February 2017).
[src:code-splitting/dynamic-loading] The Go runtime and any library functions are statically linked into the compiled binary.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This guide gives you all you need to get started with JavaScript module syntax.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] JavaScript programs started off pretty small — most of its usage in the early days was to do isolated scripting tasks, providing a bit of interactivity to your web pages where needed, so large scripts were generally not needed.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Fast forward a few years and we now have complete applications being run in browsers with a lot of JavaScript, as well as JavaScript being used in other contexts (Node.js, for example).
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Complex projects necessitate a mechanism for splitting JavaScript programs into separate modules that can be imported when needed.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Node.js has had this ability for a long time, and there are a number of JavaScript libraries and frameworks that enable module usage (for example, other CommonJS and AMD-based module systems like RequireJS, webpack, and Babel).
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] All modern browsers support module features natively without needing transpilation.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] It can only be a good thing — browsers can optimize loading of modules, making it more efficient than having to use a library and do all of that extra client-side processing and extra round trips.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] It does not obsolete bundlers like webpack, though — bundlers still do a good job at partitioning code into reasonably sized chunks, and are able to do other optimizations like minification, dead code elimination, and tree-shaking.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] To demonstrate usage of modules, we've created a set of examples that you can find on GitHub.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] These examples demonstrate a set of modules that create a `<canvas>` element on a webpage, and then draw (and report information about) different shapes on the canvas.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] These are fairly trivial, but have been kept deliberately simple to demonstrate modules clearly.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Throughout this article, we've used `.js` extensions for our module files, but in other resources you may see the `.mjs` extension used instead.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] V8's documentation recommends this, for example.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] However, we decided to keep using `.js`, at least for the moment.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] To get modules to work correctly in a browser, you need to make sure that your server is serving them with a `Content-Type` header that contains a JavaScript MIME type such as `text/javascript`.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] If you don't, you'll get a strict MIME type checking error along the lines of "The server responded with a non-JavaScript MIME type" and the browser won't run your JavaScript.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Most servers already set the correct type for `.js` files, but not yet for `.mjs` files.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Servers that already serve `.mjs` files correctly include GitHub Pages and `http-server` for Node.js.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This is OK if you are using such an environment already, or if you aren't but you know what you are doing and have access (i.e., you can configure your server to set the correct `Content-Type` for `.mjs` files).
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] It could however cause confusion if you don't control the server you are serving files from, or are publishing files for public use, as we are here.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] For learning and portability purposes, we decided to keep to `.js`.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] If you really value the clarity of using `.mjs` for modules versus using `.js` for "normal" JavaScript files, but don't want to run into the problem described above, you could always use `.mjs` during development and convert them to `.js` during your build step.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] The first thing you do to get access to module features is export them.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This is done using the `export` statement.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] You can export functions, `var`, `let`, `const`, and — as we'll see later — classes.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] They need to be top-level items: for example, you can't use `export` inside a function.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] A more convenient way of exporting all the items you want to export is to use a single export statement at the end of your module file, followed by a comma-separated list of the features you want to export wrapped in curly braces.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Once you've exported some features out of your module, you need to import them into your script to be able to use them.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] You use the `import` statement, followed by a comma-separated list of the features you want to import wrapped in curly braces, followed by the keyword `from`, followed by the *module specifier*.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] The *module specifier* provides a string that the JavaScript environment can resolve to a path to the module file.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] In a browser, this could be a path relative to the site root, which for our `basic-modules` example would be `/js-examples/module-examples/basic-modules`.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] However, here we are instead using the dot (`.`) syntax to mean "the current location", followed by the relative path to the file we are trying to find.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This is much better than writing out the entire absolute path each time, as relative paths are shorter and make the URL portable — the example will still work if you move it to a different location in the site hierarchy.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] You can see such lines in action in `main.js`.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Once you've imported the features into your script, you can use them just like they were defined inside the same file.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Import maps allow developers to instead specify almost any text they want in the module specifier when importing a module; the map provides a corresponding value that will replace the text when the module URL is resolved.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] For example, the `imports` key in the import map below defines a "module specifier map" JSON object where the property names can be used as module specifiers, and the corresponding values will be substituted when the browser resolves the module URL.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] The values must be absolute or relative URLs.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Relative URLs are resolved to absolute URL addresses using the base URL of the document containing the import map.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] The import map is defined using a JSON object inside a `<script>` element with the `type` attribute set to `importmap`.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Note that an import map only applies to the document — the specification does not cover how to apply an import map in a worker or worklet context.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] With this map you can now use the property names above as module specifiers.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] If there is no trailing forward slash on the module specifier key then the whole module specifier key is matched and substituted.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] For example, below we match bare module names, and remap a URL to another path.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] If the module specifier has a trailing forward slash then the value must have one as well, and the key is matched as a "path prefix".
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This allows remapping of whole classes of URLs.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] It is possible for multiple keys in an import map to be valid matches for a module specifier.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] For example, a module specifier of `shapes/circle/` could match the module specifier keys `shapes/` and `shapes/circle/`.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] In this case the browser will select the most specific (longest) matching module specifier key.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Import maps allow modules to be imported using bare module names (as in Node.js), and can also simulate importing modules from packages, both with and without file extensions.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] While not shown above, they also allow particular versions of a library to be imported, based on the path of the script that is importing the module.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Generally they let developers write more ergonomic import code, and make it easier to manage the different versions and dependencies of modules used by a site.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This can reduce the effort required to use the same JavaScript libraries in both browser and server.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] The following sections expand on the various features outlined above.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] In some JavaScript environments, such as Node.js, you can use bare names for the module specifier.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This works because the environment can resolve module names to a standard location in the file system.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] For example, you might use the following syntax to import the "square" module.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] To use bare names on a browser you need an import map, which provides the information needed by the browser to resolve module specifiers to URLs (JavaScript will throw a `TypeError` if it attempts to import a module specifier that can't be resolved to a module location).
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Below you can see a map that defines a `square` module specifier key, which in this case maps to a relative address value.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Module specifier map entries, where both the specifier key and its associated value have a trailing forward slash (`/`), can be used as a path-prefix.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This allows the remapping of a whole set of import URLs from one location to another.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] It can also be used to emulate working with "packages and modules", such as you might see in the Node ecosystem.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] It is possible to import `fp` above without the `.js` file extension, but you would need to create a bare module specifier key for that file, such as `lodash/fp`, rather than using the path.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This may be reasonable for just one module, but scales poorly if you wish to import many modules.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] A module specifier key doesn't have to be path — it can also be an absolute URL (or a URL-like relative path like `./`, `../`, `/`).
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This may be useful if you want to remap a module that has absolute paths to a resource with your own local resources.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Ecosystems like Node use package managers such as npm to manage modules and their dependencies.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] The package manager ensures that each module is separated from other modules and their dependencies.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] As a result, while a complex application might include the same module multiple times with several different versions in different parts of the module graph, users do not need to think about this complexity.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Import maps similarly allow you to have multiple versions of dependencies in your application and refer to them using the same module specifier.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] You implement this with the `scopes` key, which allows you to provide module specifier maps that will be used depending on the path of the script performing the import.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] With this mapping, if a script with a URL that contains `/node_modules/dependency/` imports `cool-module`, the version in `/node_modules/some/other/location/cool-module/index.js` will be used.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] The map in `imports` is used as a fallback if there is no matching scope in the scoped map, or the matching scopes don't contain a matching specifier.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] For example, if `cool-module` is imported from a script with a non-matching scope path, then the module specifier map in `imports` will be used instead, mapping to the version in `/node_modules/cool-module/index.js`.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Note that the path used to select a scope does not affect how the address is resolved.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] The value in the mapped path does not have to match the scopes path, and relative paths are still resolved to the base URL of the script that contains the import map.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Just as for module specifier maps, you can have many scope keys, and these may contain overlapping paths.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] If multiple scopes match the referrer URL, then the most specific scope path is checked first (the longest scope key) for a matching specifier.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] The browsers will fall back to the next most specific matching scoped path if there is no matching specifier, and so on.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] If there is no matching specifier in any of the matching scopes, the browser checks for a match in the module specifier map in the `imports` key.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Script files used by websites often have hashed filenames to simplify caching.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] The downside of this approach is that if a module changes, any modules that import it using its hashed filename will also need to be updated/regenerated.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This potentially results in a cascade of updates, which is wasteful of network resources.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Import maps provide a convenient solution to this problem.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Rather than depending on specific hashed filenames, applications and scripts instead depend on an un-hashed version of the module name (address).
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] An import map like the one below then provides a mapping to the actual script file.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] If `dependency_script` changes, then its hash contained in the file name changes as well.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] In this case, we only need to update the import map to reflect the changed name of the module.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] We don't have to update the source of any JavaScript code that depends on it, because the specifier in the import statement does not change.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] One exciting feature that a unified module architecture brings is the ability to load non-JavaScript resources as modules.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] For example, you can import JSON as a JavaScript object, or import CSS as a `CSSStyleSheet` object.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] You must explicitly declare what kind of resource you are importing.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] By default, the browser assumes that the resource is JavaScript, and will throw an error if the resolved resource is something else.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Browsers will also perform validation on the module type, and fail if, for example, `./data.json` does not resolve to a JSON file.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This ensures that you don't accidentally execute code when you just intend to import data.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Once imported successfully, you can now use the imported value as a normal JavaScript object or `CSSStyleSheet` object.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Now we just need to apply the `main.js` module to our HTML page.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This is very similar to how we apply a regular script to a page, with a few notable differences.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] First of all, you need to include `type="module"` in the `<script>` element, to declare this script as a module.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] You can only use `import` and `export` statements inside modules, not regular scripts.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] An error will be thrown if your `<script>` element doesn't have the `type="module"` attribute and attempts to import other modules.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] You should generally define all your modules in separate files.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Modules declared inline in HTML can only import other modules, but anything they export will not be accessible by other modules (because they don't have a URL).
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Module-defined variables are scoped to the module unless explicitly attached to the global object.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] On the other hand, globally-defined variables are available within the module.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] The page would still render `Hello`, because the global variables `text` and `document` are available in the module.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] The functionality we've exported so far has been comprised of **named exports** — each item (be it a function, `const`, etc.) has been referred to by its name upon export, and that name has been used to refer to it on import as well.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Let's look at an example as we explain how it works.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] In our basic-modules `square.js` you can find a function called `randomSquare()` that creates a square with a random color, size, and position.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This is because there is only one default export allowed per module, and we know that `randomSquare` is it.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] So far, our canvas shape drawing modules seem to be working OK.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] But what happens if we try to add a module that deals with drawing another shape, like a circle or triangle?
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] These shapes would probably have associated functions like `draw()`, `reportArea()`, etc. too; if we tried to import different functions of the same name into the same top-level module file, we'd end up with conflicts and errors.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Fortunately there are a number of ways to get around this.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] We'll look at these in the following sections.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Inside your `import` and `export` statement's curly braces, you can use the keyword `as` along with a new feature name, to change the identifying name you will use for a feature inside the top-level module.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] In our renaming directory you'll see the same module system as in the previous example, except that we've added `circle.js` and `triangle.js` modules to draw and report on circles and triangles.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] The browser would throw an error such as "SyntaxError: redeclaration of import name" (Firefox).
