[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] What style you use is up to you, however it arguably makes more sense to leave your module code alone, and make the changes in the imports.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This especially makes sense when you are importing from third party modules that you don't have any control over.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] The above method works OK, but it's a little messy and long-winded.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] An even better solution is to import each module's features inside a module object.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This grabs all the exports available inside `module.js`, and makes them available as members of an object `Module`, effectively giving it its own namespace.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] If you go to our module-objects directory, you'll see the same example again, but rewritten to take advantage of this new syntax.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] So you can now write the code just the same as before (as long as you include the object names where needed), and the imports are much neater.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] As we hinted at earlier, you can also export and import classes; this is another option for avoiding conflicts in your code, and is especially useful if you've already got your module code written in an object-oriented style.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] You can see an example of our shape drawing module rewritten with ES classes in our classes directory.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] There will be times where you'll want to aggregate modules together.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] You might have multiple levels of dependencies, where you want to simplify things, combining several submodules into one parent module.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] For an example, see our module-aggregation directory.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] In this example (based on our earlier classes example) we've got an extra module called `shapes.js`, which aggregates all the functionality from `circle.js`, `square.js`, and `triangle.js` together.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] We've also moved our submodules inside a subdirectory inside the `modules` directory called `shapes`.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] In each of the submodules, the export is of the same form, e.g.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] These grab the exports from the individual submodules and effectively make them available from the `shapes.js` module.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] A recent addition to JavaScript modules functionality is dynamic module loading.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This allows you to dynamically load modules only when they are needed, rather than having to load everything up front.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This has some obvious performance advantages; let's read on and see how it works.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This new functionality allows you to call `import()` as a function, passing it the path to the module as a parameter.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] It returns a `Promise`, which fulfills with a module object (see Creating a module object) giving you access to that object's exports.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] In the dynamic-module-imports directory we've got another example based on our classes example.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This time however we are not drawing anything on the canvas when the example loads.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Instead, we include three buttons — "Circle", "Square", and "Triangle" — that, when pressed, dynamically load the required module and then use it to draw the associated shape.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] In this example we've only made changes to our `index.html` and `main.js` files — the module exports remain the same as before.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Note that, because the promise fulfillment returns a module object, the class is then made a subfeature of the object, hence we now need to access the constructor with `Module.` prepended to it, e.g., `Module.Square( /* … */ )`.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Another advantage of dynamic imports is that they are always available, even in script environments.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Therefore, if you have an existing `<script>` tag in your HTML that doesn't have `type="module"`, you can still reuse code distributed as modules by dynamically importing it.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Top level await is a feature available within modules.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This means the `await` keyword can be used.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] It allows modules to act as big asynchronous functions meaning code can be evaluated before use in parent modules, but without blocking sibling modules from loading.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] You can find all the files and code described in this section within the `top-level-await` directory, which extends from the previous examples.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Then we'll create a module called `getColors.js` which uses a fetch request to load the `colors.json` file and return the data as an object.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] We're using the keyword `await` before specifying the constant `colors` to export.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This means any other modules which include this one will wait until `colors` has been downloaded and parsed before using it.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This is useful because the code within `main.js` won't execute until the code in `getColors.js` has run.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] However it won't block other modules being loaded.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] For instance our `canvas.js` module will continue to load while `colors` is being fetched.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] In this case, it means that the imported values are available in the module's code even before the place that declares them, and that the imported module's side effects are produced before the rest of the module's code starts running.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Still, it is considered good practice to put all your imports at the top of the code, which makes it easier to analyze dependencies.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Modules can import other modules, and those modules can import other modules, and so on.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This forms a directed graph called the "dependency graph".
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] In an ideal world, this graph is acyclic.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] In this case, the graph can be evaluated using a depth-first traversal.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Cyclic import arises if module `a` imports module `b`, but `b` directly or indirectly depends on `a`.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] The imported variable's value is only retrieved when the variable is actually used (hence allowing live bindings), and only if the variable remains uninitialized at that time will a `ReferenceError` be thrown.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] In this example, both `a` and `b` are used asynchronously.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Therefore, at the time the module is evaluated, neither `b` nor `a` is actually read, so the rest of the code is executed as normal, and the two `export` declarations produce the values of `a` and `b`.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Then, after the timeout, both `a` and `b` are available, so the two `console.log` statements also execute as normal.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This is because when JavaScript evaluates `a.js`, it needs to first evaluate `b.js`, the dependency of `a.js`.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] However, `b.js` uses `a`, which is not yet available.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] This is because the evaluation of `b.js` completes normally, so the value of `b` is available when `a.js` is evaluated.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] You should usually avoid cyclic imports in your project, because they make your code more error-prone.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] However, cyclic imports can also occur if the libraries depend on each other, which is harder to fix.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] The introduction of modules encourages the JavaScript ecosystem to distribute and reuse code in a modular fashion.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] However, that doesn't necessarily mean a piece of JavaScript code can run in every environment.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Suppose you discovered a module that generates SHA hashes of your user's password.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Can you use it in the browser front end?
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Modules still have access to global variables, as demonstrated previously.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] If the module references globals like `window`, it can run in the browser, but will throw an error in your Node.js server, because `window` is not available there.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Similarly, if the code requires access to `process` to be functional, it can only be used in Node.js.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] In order to maximize the reusability of a module, it is often advised to make the code "isomorphic" — that is, exhibits the same behavior in every runtime.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] These practices are not unique to modules.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Still, with the trend of code reusability and modularization, you are encouraged to make your code cross-platform so that it can be enjoyed by as many people as possible.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Runtimes like Node.js are also actively implementing web APIs where possible to improve interoperability with the web.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Here are a few tips that may help you if you are having trouble getting your modules to work.
[src:code-splitting/guide-modules] Feel free to add to the list if you discover more!
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] The **`import.meta`** meta-property exposes context-specific metadata to a JavaScript module.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] It contains information about the module, such as the module's URL.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] The `import.meta` object is created by the host environment, as an extensible `null`-prototype object where all properties are writable, configurable, and enumerable.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] The full URL to the module, includes query parameters and/or hash (following the `?` or `#`).
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] In browsers, this is either the URL from which the script was obtained (for external scripts), or the URL of the containing document (for inline scripts).
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] In Node.js, this is the file path (including the `file://` protocol).
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] Resolves a module specifier to a URL using the current module's URL as base.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] The `import.meta` syntax consists of the keyword `import`, a dot, and the identifier `meta`.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] Because `import` is a reserved word, not an identifier, this is not a property accessor, but a special expression syntax.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] The `import.meta` meta-property is available in JavaScript modules; using `import.meta` outside of a module (including direct `eval()` within a module) is a syntax error.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] Using query parameters in the `import` specifier allows module-specific argument passing, which may be complementary to reading parameters from the application-wide `window.location` (or on Node.js, through `process.argv`).
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] The ES module implementation in Node.js supports resolving module specifiers containing query parameters (or the hash), as in the latter example.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] However, you cannot use queries or hashes when the module is specified through the CLI command (like `node index.mjs?someURLInfo=5`), because the CLI entrypoint uses a more CommonJS-like resolution mode, treating the path as a file path rather than a URL.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] To pass parameters to the entrypoint module, use CLI arguments and read them through `process.argv` instead (like `node index.mjs --someURLInfo=5`).
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] In Node.js CommonJS modules, there's a `__dirname` variable that contains the absolute path to the folder containing current module, which is useful for resolving relative paths.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] However, ES modules cannot have contextual variables except for `import.meta`.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] Therefore, to resolve a relative file you can use `import.meta.url`.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import-meta] Note that this uses URLs rather than filesystem paths.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] The **`import()`** syntax, commonly called *dynamic import*, is a function-like expression that allows loading an ECMAScript module asynchronously and dynamically into a potentially non-module environment.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] Unlike the declaration-style counterpart, dynamic imports are only evaluated when needed, and permit greater syntactic flexibility.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] The `import()` call is a syntax that closely resembles a function call, but `import` itself is a keyword, not a function.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] You cannot alias it like `const myImport = import`, which will throw a `SyntaxError`.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] Trailing commas are only allowed if the runtime also supports `options`.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] The evaluation of the specifier is host-specified, but always follows the same algorithm as static import declarations.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] The import declaration syntax (`import something from "somewhere"`) is static and will always result in the imported module being evaluated at load time.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] Dynamic imports allow one to circumvent the syntactic rigidity of import declarations and load a module conditionally or on demand.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] The static form is preferable for loading initial dependencies, and can benefit more readily from static analysis tools and tree shaking.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] If your file is not run as a module (if it's referenced in an HTML file, the script tag must have `type="module"`), you will not be able to use static import declarations.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] On the other hand, the asynchronous dynamic import syntax is always available, allowing you to import modules into non-module environments.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] The `options` parameter allows different kinds of import options.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] Dynamic module import is not permitted in all execution contexts.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] For example, `import()` can be used in the main thread, a shared worker, or a dedicated worker, but will throw if called within a service worker or a worklet.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] A *module namespace object* is an object that describes all exports from a module.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] It is a static object that is created when the module is evaluated.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] There are two ways to access the module namespace object of a module: through a namespace import (`import * as name from moduleName`), or through the fulfillment value of a dynamic import.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] The module namespace object is a sealed object with `null` prototype.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] This means all string keys of the object correspond to the exports of the module and there are never extra keys.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] All keys are enumerable in lexicographic order (i.e., the default behavior of `Array.prototype.sort()`), with the default export available as a key called `default`.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] In addition, the module namespace object has a `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property with the value `"Module"`, used in `Object.prototype.toString()`.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] The string properties are non-configurable and writable when you use `Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptors()` to get their descriptors.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] However, they are effectively read-only, because you cannot re-assign a property to a new value.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] This behavior mirrors the fact that static imports create "live bindings" — the values can be re-assigned by the module exporting them, but not by the module importing them.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] The writability of the properties reflects the possibility of the values changing, because non-configurable and non-writable properties must be constant.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] For example, you can re-assign the exported value of a variable, and the new value can be observed in the module namespace object.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] Except in one curious case: because a promise never fulfills to a thenable, if the `my-module.js` module exports a function called `then()`, that function will automatically get called when the dynamic import's promise is fulfilled, as part of the promise resolution process.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] This aggressive caching ensures that a piece of JavaScript code is never executed more than once, even if it is imported multiple times.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] Future imports don't even result in HTTP requests or disk access.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] If you do need to re-import and re-evaluate a module without restarting the entire JavaScript environment, one possible trick is to use a unique query parameter in the module specifier.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] This works in non-browser runtimes that support URL specifiers too.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] Note that this can lead to memory leaks in a long-running application, because the engine cannot safely garbage-collect any module namespace objects.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] Currently, there is no way to manually clear the cache of module namespace objects.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] However, this is semantically not the same as dynamic import, because user-agent settings like fetch destination, CSP, or module resolution may not be applied correctly.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] Module namespace object caching only applies to modules that are loaded and linked *successfully*.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] A module is imported in three steps: loading (fetching the module), linking (mostly, parsing the module), and evaluating (executing the parsed code).
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] Only evaluation failures are cached; if a module fails to load or link, the next import may try to load and link the module again.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] The browser may or may not cache the result of the fetch operation, but it should follow typical HTTP semantics, so handling such network failures should not be different from handling `fetch()` failures.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] If your project uses packages that export ESM, you can also import them for side effects only.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] This will run the code in the package entry point file (and any files it imports) only.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] If you are destructuring the imported module namespace object, then you must rename the `default` key because `default` is a reserved word.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] This example shows how to load functionality on to a page based on a user action, in this case a button click, and then call a function within that module.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] This is not the only way to implement this functionality.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] The `import()` function also supports `await`.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] In processes such as server-side rendering, you may need to load different logic on server or in browser because they interact with different globals or modules (for example, browser code has access to web APIs like `document` and `navigator`, while server code has access to the server file system).
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] You can do so through a conditional dynamic import.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] Dynamic imports allow any expression as the module specifier, not necessarily string literals.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] Here, we load 10 modules, `/modules/module-0.js`, `/modules/module-1.js`, etc., concurrently, and call the `load` functions that each one exports.
[src:code-splitting/operators-import] Import attributes are accepted as the second parameter of the `import()` syntax.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] It’s been available across browsers since March 2023.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] The **`importmap`** value of the `type` attribute of the `<script>` element indicates that the body of the element contains an import map.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] An import map is a JSON object that allows developers to control how the browser resolves module specifiers when importing JavaScript modules.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] It provides a mapping between the text used as the module specifier in an `import` statement or `import()` operator, and the corresponding value that will replace the text when resolving the specifier.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] The JSON object must conform to the Import map JSON representation format.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] An import map is used to resolve module specifiers in static and dynamic imports, and therefore must be declared and processed before any `<script>` elements that import modules using specifiers declared in the map.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] Note that the import map applies only to module specifiers in the `import` statement or `import()` operator for modules loaded into documents; it does not apply to the path specified in the `src` attribute of a `<script>` element or to modules loaded into workers or worklets.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] For more information, see the Importing modules using import maps section in the JavaScript modules guide.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] The `src`, `async`, `nomodule`, `defer`, `crossorigin`, `integrity`, and `referrerpolicy` attributes must not be specified.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] The import map definition is not a JSON object, the `importmap` key is defined but its value is not a JSON object, or the `scopes` key is defined but its value is not a JSON object.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] Browsers generate console warnings for other cases where the import map JSON does not conform to the import map schema.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] When importing a JavaScript module, both the `import` statement and `import()` operator have a "module specifier" that indicates the module to be imported.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] A browser must be able to resolve this specifier to an absolute URL in order to import the module.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] For example, the following statements import elements from the module specifier `"https://example.com/shapes/circle.js"`, which is an absolute URL, and the module specifier `"./modules/shapes/square.js"`, which is a path relative to the base URL of the document.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] Import maps allow developers to specify (almost) any text they want in the module specifier; the map provides a corresponding value that will replace the text when the module specifier is resolved.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] The import map below defines an `imports` key that has a "module specifier map" with properties `circle` and `square`.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] A module specifier map key can also be used to remap a path prefix in a module specifier.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] Note that in this case the property and mapped path must both have a trailing forward slash (`/`).
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] We could then import a circle module as shown.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] Module specifier keys do not have to be single word names ("bare names").
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] They can also contain or end with path separators, or be absolute URLs, or be relative URL paths that start with `/`, `./`, or `../`.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] If there are several module specifier keys in a module specifier map that might match, then the most specific key will be selected (i.e., the one with the longer path/value).
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] A module specifier of `./foo/../js/app.js` would be resolved to `./js/app.js` before matching.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] This means that a module specifier key of `./js/app.js` would match the module specifier even though they are not exactly the same.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] You can use the `scopes` key to provide mappings that are only used if the script importing the module contains a particular URL path.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] If the URL of the loading script matches the supplied path, the mapping associated with the scope will be used.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] This allows different versions of the module to be used depending on what code is doing the importing.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] For example, the map below will only use the scoped map if the loading module has a URL that includes the path: "/modules/custom-shapes/".
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] If multiple scopes match the referrer URL, then the most specific scope path is used (the scope key name with the longest name).
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] The browser falls back to the next most specific scoped path if there is no matching specifier, and so on, eventually falling back to the module specifier map in the `imports` key.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] You can use the `integrity` key to provide mapping for module integrity metadata.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] This enables you to ensure the integrity of dynamically or statically imported modules.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] `integrity` also enables you to provide a fallback for top-level or preloaded modules, in case they don't already include an `integrity` attribute.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] The map keys represent module URLs, which can be absolute or relative (starting with `/`, `./`, or `../`).
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] The map values represent integrity metadata, identical to that used in `integrity` attribute values.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] For example, the map below defines integrity metadata for the `square.js` module (directly) and its bare specifier (transitively, via the `imports` key).
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] Supporting browsers can declare one or more import maps anywhere in the document, provided they are defined before any module that depends on them is loaded (some browser versions allow only a single import map declaration, which must appear before any module is loaded).
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] Internally, browsers maintain a single global import map representation.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] When multiple import maps are included in a document, their contents are merged into the global import map when they are registered.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] Module specifiers in each registered map that were already resolved beforehand are dropped.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] Subsequent resolutions of these specifiers will provide the same results as their previous resolutions.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] The `/app/helper.js` rule was ignored and not incorporated into the map.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] Similarly, module specifiers in a registered map that were already mapped to URLs in the global map are dropped; their previous mapping prevails.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] The `/app/helper/` rule was dropped from the second map.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] The following is a "formal" definition of the import map JSON representation.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] The import map must be a valid JSON object that can define any of the optional keys `imports`, `scopes` and `integrity`.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] Each key's value must be an object, which may be empty.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] The value is a module specifier map, which provides the mappings between module specifier text that might appear in an `import` statement or `import()` operator, and the text that will replace it when the specifier is resolved.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] This is the fallback map that is searched for matching module specifiers if no `scopes` path URLs match, or if module specifier maps in matching `scopes` paths do not contain a key that matches the module specifier.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] A "module specifier map" is a valid JSON object where the *keys* are text that may be present in the module specifier when importing a module, and the corresponding *values* are the URLs or paths that will replace this text when the module specifier is resolved to an address.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] Defines a valid JSON object where the *keys* are strings containing valid absolute or relative URLs (starting with `/`, `./`, or `../`), and the corresponding *values* are valid integrity metadata.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] If the URL of a script importing or preloading a module matches a key in the `integrity` object, the corresponding integrity metadata is applied to the script's fetch options, unless they already have integrity metadata attached to them.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] Scopes define path-specific module specifier maps, allowing the choice of map to depend on the path of the code importing the module.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] The scopes object is a valid JSON object where each property is a `<scope key>`, which is a URL path, with a corresponding value that is a `<module specifier map>`.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] If the URL of a script importing a module matches a `<scope key>` path, then the `<module specifier map>` value associated with the key is checked for matching specifiers first.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] If there are multiple matching scope keys, then the value associated with the most specific/nested scope paths are checked for matching module specifiers first.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] The fallback module specifier map in `imports` is used if there are no matching module specifier keys in any of the matching scoped module specifier maps.
[src:code-splitting/type-importmap] Note that the scope does not change how an address is resolved; relative addresses are always resolved to the import map base URL.
